"Draft Degregulation BillCity &amp; Guilds response\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSeptember 2013 \n&#xa0;\nCity &amp; Guilds is a leading vocational awarding organisation for work-based qualifications, committed to offering high quality qualifications across a wide range of industrial sectors, \nthrough 8500 colleges and training providers worldwide\n. \nWe value the provision of qualifications to a high standard and support \nany\n work to ensure \nthese \nstandards through the strategic regulation of \nawarding organisation\ns and qualifications.\n&#xa0;\nTwo million people every year take City &amp; Guilds qualifications, which span levels from basic skills to the highest levels of professional achievement, and are designed to help people gai\nn the skills employers’ value. \nCity &amp; Guilds is also a major innovator in the field of electro\nnic assessment (e-assessment). \nMore than four million on-line tests have been taken by candidates entering fo\nr City &amp; Guilds qualifications.\n&#xa0;\nWe welcome the opportunity to provide comment\ns\n to this \ncall for evidence and will refer specifically to areas of the Bill affecting education and training. We\n look forward to working with \nthe Joint Committee\n on further developments.\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nSummary of response&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nResponse to Call for Evidence&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nRegulators\n to “have\n regard” to the desirability of \n“promoting economic growth”\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nPower to disapply legislation “no longer of practical use”\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nApprenticeships \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nReduction of burdens: FE and HE education \n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n Skills Commission (2010) \nTeacher Training in Vocational Education\n. London: Policy Connect, p 9\n City &amp; Guilds Centre for Skills Development. \nHow to teach vocational education: A theory of vocational pedagogy\n. London,\n 2012.\n"